                        Silius Italicus of the warres betwene Annibal, &amp; Scipio in Latin verse: much like Lucan of the warres betwene Pompey, &amp; Ca[e]sar. 
                        But giue mee still Liuie of the one, &amp; Ca[e]sar himself of the other: in comparison of whome Silius, &amp; Lucan ar but trifles. No other
                        warres in the world , comparable to theise twoe. (The next, the terrible warres betwene Sylla, &amp; Marius: who tawght Ca[e]sar his lesson:
                        brauely also displayed in Latin verses bie Three of M. Smythes, &amp; mie gallant poets. of Homers &amp; Virgils wing.
                    </marginalia_text>
